<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,654,895]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,654,679]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body squat. In female, antenna very short and F3 considerably stout (
<emphasis box="[1060,1100,655,678]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">e.g.</emphasis>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1114,1195,654,679]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1207,1229]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,503,1185]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[151,1436,503,1185]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 12. Pediobius facialis (Giraud 1863). a: female, body in dorsal view; b: female, body in lateral view; c: male, body in dorsal view; d: female, hind leg; e: female, antenna; f: male, antenna; g: female, fore wing. Scale bar: a – c, 0.5 mm; d – f, 0.2 mm; g, 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375771/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
e), but in male less so (
<emphasis box="[160,200,692,715]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">e.g.</emphasis>
, 12f). Mesoscutum and scutellum finely reticulate, and more finely so in notaular depressions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,654,895]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,411,726,751]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Species included.</emphasis>
Although there might be some confusion on the relationship among 
<taxonomicName box="[1274,1392,726,751]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="facialis">
<emphasis box="[1274,1392,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. facialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachycerus">
<emphasis box="[1415,1429,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,290,762,787]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">brachycerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[348,460,763,787]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grunini">
<emphasis box="[348,362,764,787]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[378,460,764,787]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">grunini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Nikol'skaya), we follow 
<bibRefCitation author="Boucek" box="[760,942,762,787]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Boucek, Z. (1965 a) Studies of European Eulophidae, IV: Pediobius WALK. and two allied genera (Hymenoptera). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 36, 5 - 90." type="journal article" year="1965" yearSuffix="a">Bouček (1965a)</bibRefCitation>
and place them in the same species group. Besides, two Chinese species, 
<taxonomicName box="[508,647,799,822]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="narangae">
<emphasis box="[508,522,799,822]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[540,647,799,822]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">narangae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[710,850,798,823]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tortricida">
<emphasis box="[710,724,799,822]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[742,850,798,823]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">tortricida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also included in this species group. However, instead of the &quot; 
<taxonomicName box="[336,474,834,859]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachycerus">
<emphasis box="[336,474,834,859]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">brachycerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group&quot;, we call this species group as the &quot; 
<taxonomicName box="[996,1079,834,859]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="facialis">
<emphasis box="[996,1079,834,859]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">facialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group&quot; (ref. remarks under 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachycerus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. brachycerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
